# =============================================================================
# keystore.properties.example – template for release code-signing
# =============================================================================
#
# WHAT THIS IS
#   A template for the (git-ignored) file `android/keystore.properties`, which
#   supplies the release signing key to the Gradle build. It is read by the
#   `signingConfigs { create("release") }` block in app/build.gradle.kts.
#
# WHEN YOU NEED IT
#   ONLY for producing a SIGNED artifact for Google Play (a signed APK via
#   `make release`, or a signed App Bundle via `make bundle`). You do NOT need it
#   for ordinary development (the debug build is signed with the auto-generated
#   Android debug key) and you do NOT need it for F-Droid (F-Droid signs the APK
#   with its own key). Without this file and without the environment variables
#   below, the release build stays UNSIGNED — which is the intended default.
#
# HOW TO USE IT
#   1. Create a release keystore once (replace the placeholders):
#
#        keytool -genkeypair -v \
#          -keystore ~/potillus-release.jks \
#          -alias potillus \
#          -keyalg RSA -keysize 4096 -validity 10000
#
#      Keep BOTH the keystore file and the passwords safe and OFF the repository.
#      Losing the key means you can never update the Play listing again (unless
#      you enrolled in Google Play App Signing with a separate upload key).
#
#   2. Copy this file to `keystore.properties` (same directory) and fill in the
#      four values below. `keystore.properties` is git-ignored, so it is never
#      committed.
#
#        cp keystore.properties.example keystore.properties
#        $EDITOR keystore.properties
#
#   3. Build a signed artifact:
#
#        make release   # signed app-release.apk   (was app-release-unsigned.apk)
#        make bundle    # signed app-release.aab    (for Google Play upload)
#
# ENVIRONMENT-VARIABLE ALTERNATIVE (for CI)
#   Each property has an environment-variable equivalent that takes PRECEDENCE
#   over the file, so a CI runner can inject the secrets without writing a file:
#
#        storeFile      ← POTILLUS_KEYSTORE_FILE
#        storePassword  ← POTILLUS_KEYSTORE_PASSWORD
#        keyAlias       ← POTILLUS_KEY_ALIAS
#        keyPassword    ← POTILLUS_KEY_PASSWORD
#
# FORMAT
#   Plain `key=value` lines (java.util.Properties). `storeFile` is resolved
#   relative to the android/ directory; an absolute path also works.
# =============================================================================

# Path to the release keystore (relative to android/, or absolute).
storeFile=../potillus-release.jks

# Password protecting the keystore file itself.
storePassword=CHANGE_ME

# Alias of the key entry inside the keystore (the `-alias` from keytool).
keyAlias=potillus

# Password protecting that specific key entry (often identical to storePassword).
keyPassword=CHANGE_ME
